$ Graphviz (dot) examples


{ Dotted edges etc

  → tools/Graphviz/examples/dotted-edge.png

  gh|about-Graphviz|/examples/dotted-edge.dot||

}
{ Shape: record vs. plaintext

  If the `shape` attribute is set to `record`, the text of the `label` is layouted in tabular form.

  The vertical bar (`|`) starts a new row or column.

  The curly braces `{ ... }` change (flip) the direction of `|`.

  gh|about-Graphviz|/examples/img/shape-record-vs-plaintext.png||

  gh|about-Graphviz|/examples/shape-record-vs-plaintext.dot||

}
{ Multiple edges

  Normally, a dependency (an edge) is declared with an arrow: `Node1 -> Node2`. Multiple nodes can be listed in curly braces, thus declaring multple edges in one go.

  → tools/Graphviz/examples/multiple-edges.png

  gh|about-Graphviz|/examples/multiple-edges.dot||

}
{ Left, mid and right aligned text

  `\l` makes the preceeding text right aligned, `\n` makes it centered and `\r` makes it left aligned.

  → tools/Graphviz/examples/left-mid-right-aligned-text.png

  gh|about-Graphviz|/examples/left-mid-right-aligned-text.dot||

}
{ Giving the graph a caption

  With `label`, the graph can be given a caption:

  → tools/Graphviz/examples/label.png

  gh|about-Graphviz|/examples/label.dot||

}
{ HTML like labels

  If the text of label is enclosed in `<…>` rather than in `"…"`, the text is treated as HTML:

  → tools/Graphviz/examples/label-html-like.png

  gh|about-Graphviz|/examples/label-html-like.dot||

}
{ rank

  `{ rank=same node_1 node_2 … } specifies that the specified nodes have the same rank, that is, that their diestance from the top or left
  border is equal.

  → tools/Graphviz/examples/rank.png

  gh|about-Graphviz|/examples/rank.dot||

}
